Name: Australia Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1901 To Dec 1930
Monthly From Jan 1931 To Dec 1953
Annual From Dec 1954 To Dec 1963
Monthly From Jan 1964 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Source: B.R. Mitchell, International Historical Statistics, Africa, Asia & Oceania, 1750-1993,p.111; League of Nations, Monthly Statistical Bulletin (1931-1945), United Nations,Monthly Statistical Bulletin, 1946-1953) Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (1964--)
Notes: Unemployed persons are defined as persons aged 15 years and over who were not employed during the reference week, and: - had actively looked for full-time or part-time work at any time in the four weeks up to the end of the reference week, and were available for work in the reference week; or - were waiting to start a new job within four weeks from the end of the reference week and could have started in the reference week if the job had been available then. The data are obtained from the Labor Force Survey which includes all persons aged, 15 years and over except: members of the permanent defense forces; certain diplomatic personnel of overseas governments, customarily excluded from census and estimated population counts; overseas residents in Australia; and members of non-Australian defense forces (and their dependents) stationed in Australia. In the Labor Force Survey, coverage rules are applied which aim to ensure that each person is associated with only one dwelling, and hence has only one chance of selection. The coverage rules are necessarily a balance between theoretical and operational considerations. Nevertheless, the chance of a person being enumerated at two separate dwellings in the survey is considered to be negligible. The Labor Force Survey is conducted monthly. Interviews are generally conducted during the two weeks beginning on the Monday between the 6th and the 12th of each month, with the information obtained relating to the week before the interview (that is, the reference week). Core estimates from the Labor Force Survey are seasonally adjusted. These include: full-time unemployment by sex and age (15-19, 20+); part-time unemployment by sex; unemployment by State and sex; and duration of unemployment by sex. The Labor Force Survey follows closely the international recommendations set out by the International Labor Organization (ILO) for measuring unemployment.

Name: Austria Unemployment Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1931 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on the number of persons registered at employment offices on the last day of each month, or the last working day prior to this date. Unemployed persons are Austrian residents, who are allowed, and are ready and willing, to take up a job immediately; who ask the AMS for mediation and are not already holding a job (exceptions are possible). The age limit is between leaving compulsory education (age 15) and pension age (56,5-61,5 for women and 61,5-65 for men). Registration at employment offices is necessary in order to receive unemployment benefits and help for placement. Data are not seasonally adjusted. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: Belgium Unemployment Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1921 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: The standard unemployment rate published by the BNB is an estimate of the standard unemployment rate following ILO guidelines for the definition of unemployment, as adapted by Eurostat. The estimate is made on the basis of a proxy composed of all fully unemployed persons receiving unemployment benefits and registered with unemployment agencies, other unemployed persons who are required to register and unemployed persons seeking independent work who voluntarily register. The latter data are forwarded by the National Employment Office (ONE) and are adjusted to the annual labor forces survey definitions (a correction ratio of 0.6935 is applied to the ONE series of total unemployment for the current year). This unemployment rate is comparable across the various European Community countries. The BNB calculates the unemployment rate, using the methodology established by Eurostat. The rates published are seasonally adjusted and covers all economic sectors. Actual numbers of unemployed persons also are published. Data refer to the situation as of end of month. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: Brazil Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1976 To Dec 1989
Monthly From Jan 1990 To Jan 2020
Metadata:
The Unemployment data collection and definition was revised in October 2001 creating a series break in the data. The data before October 2001 and after are not directly comparable.
Notes: The presented data are for the population 15 years of age and older in number of persons and rates. The unemployment indicators disseminated are: number of unemployed persons (in the reference week); unemployed rate (in the reference week and in the reference period of 30 days); unemployed rate (in the reference week) by industry sector (of the last paid job) and by gender; unemployed rate (in the reference week) of the dwelling chiefs; number of unemployed persons (in the reference week) plus number of employed persons who actually did not receive remuneration or received less than one minimum wage from the main job in the reference month, as a percentage of the economically active population. An supplementary indicator available is the average time of seeking work.Nowadays unemployment rates (in the reference week) are already available seasonally adjusted.The data come from the "Pesquisa Mensal de Emprego - PME" [Monthly Employment Survey (PME)], which is a household sample survey. Since 1980 the PME is carried out monthly in six metropolitan areas (Recife, Salvador, Belo Horizonte, Rio de Janeiro, SÃ£o Paulo and Porto Alegre), which together represent around 25% of the total population of the Country and 26% of the population 15 years of age and older. Since 1999 PME is also carried out in the metropolitan area of Curitiba. The results are produced for each one of the seven metropolitan areas and for the set of the six metropolitan areas surveyed since 1980.

Name: Canada Unemployment Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1919 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Source: Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
Notes: Data are disseminated on unemployment numbers (thousands of persons). "Unemployed persons" are defined as those, 15 years of age and older, who, during the reference week, were available for work and were either on temporary layoff, had looked for work in the past four weeks, or had a job to start within the next four weeks. The data are obtained from the monthly Canadian Labor Force Survey (L.F.S.), which is representative of the Canadian non-institutional population 15 years of age and older. The survey coverage excludes residents of long-term care health facilities (more than six months), members of the Canadian armed forces, persons living on Indian reserves, and those in the North West Territories, the Yukon and Nunavut. The survey uses a reference week concept to measure labor market activity, and the reference week is typically the week containing the fifteenth day of the month. The L.F.S. provides a number of key labor market measures that generally conform to ILO concepts and definitions. The data are seasonally adjusted.

Name: Chile Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1966 To Feb 1986
Monthly From Mar 1986 To Nov 2020
Metadata:
Source: Central Bank of Chile

Notes: Data on unemployment are published as rates. Estimates of the levels of unemployed persons are also disseminated in thousands of persons. The data refer to persons who have looked for a job once or more during the two months previous to the survey and have worked for less than one hour during the week prior to that of the survey. First time job seekers are also included. The information is presented for the whole nation as well as by region and are based on sample data obtained according to the recommendations of the International Labor Organisation (ILO). The current sample, which is based on the 1992 Population and Housing Census, is probabilistic and encompasses two stages whereby geographical units (with predefined boundaries) selected in an initial stage are called sections, and sample units selected in a second stage correspond to occupied private dwellings within the sections.This sample covers the whole country. The survey is conducted quarterly, but divided in three segments in each of the the three months of the quarter.

Name: Czech Republic Unemployment Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1993 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated (as a number and as a percentage of laborforce) on registered unemployment and vacancies as on the last day of the month. The data cover the entire economy.  "Unemployed persons" are defined as those citizens registered by the labor offices in the Czech Republic who want to and can work, and who have applied for jobs. This information is declared on the individual applications presented to the labor offices. To be able to register at the labor offices, a person must be over 15 years of age. There is no fixed upper age limit for registration. "Available unemployed" are defined as unemployed persons registrated by the labor office who are able to take a job immediately, i.e. excluding those who are engaged in an education program, basic military and civilian service, are not sick, do not receive child-care benefit, old-age pension.   Employment rate under registration (as a percentage of laborforce) is counted from available job seekers. Breakdowns are disseminated down to the district level. The data are not seasonally adjusted. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: Denmark Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1910 To Jul 1931
Monthly From Aug 1931 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on the unemployment that includes all persons who are out of work, seeking work, and available for work. The data cover the whole country, excluding Greenland and the Faeroe islands. The unemployment figures are extracted from CRAM, the central register for labour market statistics. CRAM includes both people who are insured against unemployment and people who are not. The age limit to register as unemployed is between 16 and 66 years. Data are disseminated as the number of persons registered as unemployed and as a percentage of the labour force. The reference period is a month, based on weekly averages.  Data are disseminated in both original and seasonally adjusted form. Source: Eurostat. Name: Finland Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1958 To Dec 1959
Monthly From Jan 1960 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Source: Statistics Finland.
Notes: Data are disseminated in thousands of unemployed persons. Unemployed persons are defined as all persons who for the whole survey week were without work, had been seeking a job actively in the past four weeks as an employee or a self-employed person and could accept a job within two weeks. Persons without a job and waiting to start a job within two weeks are also recorded as unemployed. Those who have been laid-off for an indefinite period from their work and meet the job seeking and job acceptance criteria are also considered as unemployed. Persons on unemployment pension are counted as unemployed only if seeking a job.The data cover the population aged 15-74 years residing in the country. The main variables are seasonally adjusted.

Name: France Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1895 To Jun 1897
Monthly From Jul 1897 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Data are disseminated as: Number of end-of month unemployed persons (according to I.L.O. criteria) for metropolitan France (including Corsica); Unemployment rate: number of end-of month unemployed persons according to I.L.O. criteria relative to labour force (15-65 years). Data are also disseminated by sex and age group.
Data are based upon the results of the annual Labor Force Survey (LFS), carried out in March of each year. Data are updated monthly with a level of I.L.O. unemployment by means of an econometric equation using primary monthly data on the number of unemployed persons (number of month-end job seekers registered at the Agence Nationale pour l'Emploi (national employment agency, ANPE), and the number of temporary workers. Date are seasonally adjusted. Source: Eurostat. Name: Germany Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1887 To Dec 1920
Monthly From Jan 1921 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on total unemployment figures, expressed both as the number of unemployed and as a percentage (the unemployment rate). The "unemployed" cover job seekers not employed, or employed for less than 15 hours per week, in the age group 15-64, excluding those engaged in an education program and those who are incapacitated or in receipt of an old-age pension. The data are based on applications (Bewerberangebote) submitted by the unemployed to the local employment offices. The data are as reported at the end of each month by the local employment labour offices. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Name: Hong Kong Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Quarterly From Mar 1992 To Mar 1997
Monthly From Apr 1997 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Source: Hong Kong Monetary Authority

Notes: Labour force statistics are compiled on the basis of data obtained from the General Household Survey which covers the land-based non-institutional population of Hong Kong. The survey does not cover inmates of institutions and persons living on board vessels. The current sample size is about 24,000 households per three-month period. A rotational replicate sample design is adopted such that about half of the quarters sampled in the current month were enumerated three months ago.

The definition of unemployment used in the survey follows closely that recommended by the International Labour Organization. The unemployed population comprises all unemployed persons. For a person aged 15 or over to be classified as unemployed, that person should:
(a) not have had a job and should not have performed any work for pay or profit during the seven days before enumeration; and
(b) have been available for work during the seven days before enumeration; and
(c) have sought work during the thirty days before enumeration.
However, if a person aged 15 or over fulfils the conditions (a) and (b) above but has not sought work during the thirty days before enumeration because he/she believes that work is not available, he/she is still classified as unemployed, being regarded as a so-called "discouraged worker". Notwithstanding the above, the following types of persons are also classified as unemployed:
(a) persons without a job, have sought work but have not been available for work because of temporary sickness; and
(b) persons without a job, have been available for work but have not sought work because they:
(i) have made arrangements to take up a new job or to start business at a subsequent date; or
(ii) were expecting to return to their original jobs (e.g. casual workers are usually called back to work when service is needed).

Numbers of unemployed persons are available in original terms only, while unemployment rates are available in both original terms and seasonally adjusted terms (i.e. adjusted for seasonal variations using the X-11 ARIMA method). In the General Household Survey, a "shifting survey moment" approach is used in data collection. The reference periods for not having a job and for availability for work are set at "seven days before enumeration", while the reference period for seeking work is set at "thirty days before enumeration". The data collected in a month refer to the average for the entire month.

Name: Italy Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1947 To Jun 1953
Monthly From Jul 1953 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on the number of unemployed persons and on the Unemployment rate. The Unemployment rate is obtained from the ratio between persons seeking employment and the total labour force as measured by the LFS. The data are obtained from the Labor Force Survey (LFS), which is addressed to a sample of resident population living in private households throughout Italy. People living in collctive households are therefore excluded. The sample selection is carried out in two stages. At first stage, approximately 1,300 out of the over 8,000 municipalities are selected. At second stage, almost 77,000 households, corrisponding to about 200,000 individuals, are sampled in the selected municipalities. The sample represents Italian population of about 20 million households and 57 million persons.  The LFS is carried out continuously, at a rate of 6,000 household interviews per week. The definition adopted for the principal aggregates correspond to those recommended by the ILO and adopted at the EU level by EUROSTAT.  "Unemployment" includes persons aged 15 to 74 not employed in the reference week who were actively seeking employment in the four weeks preceding interview and were immediately available (within 2 weeks) to accept a position should one be forthcoming.  The LFS data are seasonally adjusted using the TRAMO-SEATS procedure (version: June 1998). Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: Japan Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1880 To Dec 1930
Monthly From Jan 1931 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Pre-1930 data are from MIC (2009: Table 19-1). Data are disseminated on the number of unemployed persons. Unemployed persons" are defined as persons 15 years old and over who did not work at all during the survey week, but were currently available for work and were actively seeking a job or were waiting for the results of past job-seeking activity. The data are derived from the Labour Force Survey, which is a monthly household survey, The survey covers all persons 15 years old and over, usually resident in Japan, except the foreign diplomatic corps, their staff and dependents, and foreign military personnel and their dependents. The data are compiled in accordance with the international guidelines set out by the ILO. Data are also disseminated on the number of unemployed persons broken down by age, preference for employment as primary or secondary activity, and the reason for seeking a job, and ratio of unemployed in the labour force by age and relationship to the head of the household. The data are presented in both a seasonally-adjusted and a nonseasonally-adjusted format. The reference period to which the unemployment data refer to is one week ending on the last day of each month, except December for which it is one week from 20 to 26. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: South Korea Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1960 To Dec 1965
Monthly From Jan 1966 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on the absolute number of persons unemployed and on the unemployment rate. "Unemployed persons" are defined as all persons, aged 15 years and over, who are not working but are actively looking, and are available, for work during the reference week, which includes the 15th of the month. The data cover all persons who usually reside within the country at the time of enumeration, but exclude the armed forces, prisoners, and foreigners. The "unemployment rate" is defined as the number of unemployed expressed as a percent of the workforce. The data are obtained from a sample survey, the Economically Active Population Survey, which is conducted by the CAPI (Computer Assisted Personal interviewing) through the regular interviewers of NSO. The survey covers about 33,000 households, accounting for 0.2 percent of the total households of Korea. The data are published in both an unadjusted and seasonally-adjusted format.

Name: Netherlands Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1911 To Dec 1918
Monthly From Jan 1919 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on the three month centered moving average of the number of unemployed labour force. The unemployed labour force are persons aged 15-64 who have accepted work for at least 12 hours a week, or willing to work at least 12 hours a week, who are available and actively seeking work for at least 12 hours a week. The data are published in both a non-seasonally adjusted and a seasonally adjusted format. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: New Zealand Unemployment Rate Quarterly
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1891 To Mar 1970
Quarterly From Jun 1970 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Definition: Data refer to persons enrolled as unemployed jobseeker with the Employment Services Division of the Department of Labor. The unemployed must be currently not in employment, available for and willing to accept full-time work (any job requiring the attendance of the worker for 30 hours or more each week). Vacation workers, i.e full-time students seeking full-time work during the summer vacation period only, are also included in the series. Coverage: Geographical coverage is the whole country except off sfore islands. Persons working less than 20 hours a week or persons working between 20 and 30 hours per week and enrolled with the Employment Services are also considered as registered unemployed if they are available and willing to work more than 30 hours. Collection: All those aged 15-60 and meeting the definitional criteria are allowed to register for work at the public employment service offices. Calculation: Monthly data refer to end of period. Quarterly and annual data are averages of the monthly figures. Source: Department of Labor, New Zealand Level: survey-based, '000 Definition: Data refer to all persons of working age who during the reference week were without a paid job, were available for work and had actively looked for work in the past four weeks ending with the reference week or had a new job to start within four weeks. A person whose only job search method in the previous four weeks has been to look at job advertisements in the newspapers is not considered to be actively seeking work. Collection: Data are compiled from the results of the Quarterly Household Labor Force Survey, see Civilian Employment.
Source: Statistics New Zealand

Name: Norway Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1904 To Dec 1912
Monthly From Jan 1913 To Dec 1941
Quarterly From Mar 1942 To Dec 1945
Monthly From Jan 1946 To Dec 1957
Quarterly From Mar 1958 To Dec 1959
Monthly From Jan 1960 To Dec 1968
Quarterly From Mar 1969 To May 1989
Monthly From Jun 1989 To Nov 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Data are disseminated on the number of unemployed persons and on the unemployed as a percentage of the labor force. "Unemployed persons" are defined as persons aged 16-74 who are not employed in the survey week, but who have been seeking work during the preceding four weeks, and are available for work within the next two weeks. Monthly data from 1913 to 1970 is for unemployment among trade unionists. Source: Norway Statistical Yearbook.
The unemployment data, covering all the unemployed population of Norway in line with ILO definitions and guidelines from Eurostat, are obtained from weekly labor force sample surveys (LFS). The surveys are based on interviews with selected groups of individuals aged 16 to 74, using a questionnaire that has been used since the second quarter of 1988 (at which time questions about underemployment were added). The LFS is a continuous survey. The quarterly unemployment data are derived from the average of the monthly data which in turn are calculated from the average of the relevant weekly LFS data.
The data are disseminated on both an unadjusted and a seasonally-adjusted format. The seasonally-adjusted data are calculated by using the X12ARIMA method applying a 3-month moving average. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Name: Singapore Unemployment Rate Quarterly
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1968 To Dec 1991
Quarterly From Mar 1992 To Dec 2019
Metadata:
Source: Ministry of Manpower, Singapore
Notes: Data are disseminated on the unemployment rate and on the number of unemployed persons. "Unemployed persons" are defined as persons aged fifteen years and over who were not working during the survey reference period but were available for work and were actively looking for a job. They include persons who were not working but were taking steps to start their own business or taking up a new job after the reference period. The "unemployment rate" is the number of unemployed persons expressed as a percentage of the labour force aged 15 years and over. The statistics on unemployment are obtained from the quarterly sample survey of private households conducted by the Manpower Research and Statistics Department, Ministry of Manpower. The survey excludes construction workers living in worksites; persons commuting daily from abroad to work in Singapore; persons living in dormitories or workers' quarters at the workplace; persons living in institutional households; and persons on board ships and boats. The March, September, and December surveys effectively cover at least 6,000 households each. The June survey effectively covers at least 25,000 households. The data refer to the last month of each quarter, that is, March, June, September, and December. The Department follows the international guidelines set out by the ILO for measuring unemployment. The data are published in both an unadjusted and a seasonally-adjusted format.

Name: Spain Unemployment Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1964 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on the number of unemployed and on the unemployment rate. "Unemployed persons" are defined as those persons aged 16 or over who, in the reference week (usually, the week immediately preceeding the week of the interview), were out of work, available to start to work, and actively looking for a job. Persons who, while out of work, are available to start to work and have already found a job but have not yet started to work, are also defined as "unemployed". The "unemployment rate" is defined as the number of unemployed persons in relation to the number of active persons. The data are derived from the Active Population Survey, which covers the whole of the national territory and approximately 99% of the population. The survey is addressed to family dwellings, and therefore does not include persons living in collective households (hotels, convents, prisons, etc.). The survey is carried out continuously, at the rate of 5,000 interviews per week. The sample contains 64,000 dwellings per quarter and around 200,000 people, that is, about 0.5% of the population.The Active Population Survey follows the ILO methodology. The data refer to the average number of unemployed persons for the quarter. The data are not seasonally adjusted. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: Sweden Unemployment Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1919 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Monthly unemployment data derived from the Labour Force Survey (LFS) are disseminated as a number of unemployed persons and as a percentage of the labour force. The population in the LFS consists of all those present in Sweden who are in the civil registration system and who are 16-64 years of age. The data are obtained from a monthly sample of 17,000 people and cover all the weeks in a given month.
The following groups are defined as being "unemployed": Persons who were not employed during the reference week, but who were willing and able to work and have sought work (or would have sought work but were temporarily prevented from seeking work) during the last four weeks, including the reference week. Persons who are waiting to start a new job within four weeks. Seasonally adjusted data are also published. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: Switzerland Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1926 To Jul 1931
Monthly From Aug 1931 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Source: Swiss National Bank.
Notes: The data compiled and published cover registered unemployed, registered job seekers and registered persons who are not unemployed.
The statistics include unemployed persons as well as persons who are not unemployed but have registered with a regional placement office and are looking for a new job, according to the following definitions: registered unemployed persons: all registered job-seekers who are without work and immediately (as a rule within 30 days) available for employment; registered persons who are not unemployed: all registered job seekers who are either not immediately available for work or who already have a job. The following distinctions are made in this context: (1) persons in programs of temporary employment, (2) persons in retraining or further training programs, (3) persons with an interim source of income (4) others seeking work who are not unemployed. The reference date for the data is the last day of the month.
Until 1999, calculated on the basis of advance registrations for partial unemployment; as of 2000, on the basis of partial unemployment benefits paid out by unemployment offices.
Until 1983, fully unemployed persons; as of 1984, fully or partly unemployed persons.
Labour force in terms of the resident population until 2009: cf. time series, table N3; as of 2010: 4,322,899 persons
Until 1983, job vacancies for full-time positions; as of 1984, job vacancies for full-time and part-time positions.
As of June 2009, job vacancies registered at the regional employment centres are being kept on the books for a longer period.

Name: Great Britain Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1755 To Dec 1887
Monthly From Jan 1888 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Data from 1755 to 1856 are from The Bank of England, Three Centuries of Data, table A27. The series for the United Kingdom is based upon the percentage of unemployed trade union members in the building trades from 1888 to May 1923 and amount insured workers from June 1923 to 1948.
Data are disseminated on the number of persons claiming unemployment-related benefits at Jobcentre Plus local offices who have declared that they are unemployed, capable of, available for, and actively seeking work during the week in which their claim is made. Only those aged between 16 and 60 are eligible to claim unemployment-related benefits. Claimant count rates for UK, countries and Government Office Regions express the number of claimants who are resident in each area as a percentage of the sum of Workforce Jobs (defined as employee jobs, the self-employed, HM Forces and participants in Government-supported training programmes) and the claimant count. All sectors of the economy are covered. Claimant count proportions for sub-regional data express the number of people claiming Jobseeker's Allowance as a percentage of the working age population resident in that area. The reference period is the second Thursday of every month. The data are published in both unadjusted and seasonally adjusted form. See also the separate DSBB page for Unemployment - Labour Force Survey. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: United States U-3 Total unemployed, as a percent of the civilian labor force
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1890 To Apr 1929
Monthly From May 1929 To Jan 2021
Metadata:
Notes: Data are disseminated as levels (number of unemployed) and as a rate (defined as the proportion of the labor force which is unemployed).
"Unemployed persons" are defined as being all persons who had no employment during the reference week , were available for work, except for temporary illness, and had made specific efforts to find employment some time during the 4-week-period ending with the reference week. Persons who were waiting to be recalled to a job from which they had been paid off need not have been looking for work to be classified as unemployed. The data are compiled using information from the monthly Current Population Survey (CPS) which covers the civilian noninstitutional population 16 years and older. Each month about 55,000 occupied household units are eligible for interview. Part of the sample is changed each month, and the rotation plan provides for three-fourths of the sample to be common from one month to the next, and one-half to be common with the same month a year earlier. The reference week for the survey is the calendar week (Sunday through Saturday) that includes the 12th day of the month. The data are published in both an unadjusted and a seasonally-adjusted format.Source: Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis. The data is collected from the FRED database. The FRED database uses data from the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System, the Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia, the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, The White House Council of Economic Advisors and Office of Management and Budget, the Congressional Budget Office, the U.S. Department of Commerce, the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, the Bureau of Labor Statistics and the U.S. Department of the Treasury.

Name: Estonia Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1990 To Dec 2000
Quarterly From Mar 2001 To Dec 2014
Monthly From Jan 2015 To Nov 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data in thousands of persons (period average) are disseminated on the estimated number of unemployed persons and the unemployment rate broken down by gender and age group and by urban/rural population.   A person is considered unemployed if, during the reference week, he or she simultaneously met the following conditions: is without work (does not work anywhere at the moment and is not temporarily absent from work); is currently available within two weeks for work if there should be work; and is actively seeking work. The data are compiled on the basis of the Estonian Labour Force Survey (ELFS), which was first conducted in 1995. In 1997-1999, the ELFS was conducted annually in the second quarter of each year. Effective 2000, the ELFS is a continuous survey providing quarterly and annual results. The reference weeks are spread uniformly throughout the entire year.  The target population of the survey consists of the working-age residents of Estonia (aged 15-74 as of 1 January of the year). All population categories and geographic areas are included. The survey is in compliance with the ILO methodology. The data are not seasonally adjusted. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Statistical agencies within each country disseminate their national data to Eurostat in order that it can be made available in a consistent format.

Name: Russia Unemployment Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1992 To Nov 2020
Metadata:
Source: Federal State Statistics Service, Russian Federation

Notes: Data are disseminated on the estimated number of unemployed persons in the Russian Federation. Unemployed persons include those in the age range established for the measurement of economic activity who, during the period in question, simultaneously met the following criteria: - had no job (profitable occupation); - were seeking for a job; and - were ready to start work during the reference period. Pupils, students, pensioners, and disabled persons are considered unemployed if they were seeking for job and were ready to start it. The data are obtained from the following sources: - quarterly labour force surveys; - monthly official data on the number of persons who have no job registered by the employment offices; - tendencies of changes in the unemployment ratio according to the data of the labour force surveys; and - number of persons who have no job registered by the employment offices on the date of the labour force survey. The sample labour force survey is conducted quarterly in all the Russian regions. The planned sample is approximately 65,000 persons aged 15-72 quarterly or 0.06% of the total population of these age groups or approximately 260,000 persons calculated on an annual basis. The labor force survey is performed once per quarter as of the last week of the second month of the quarter, i.e., February, May, August, and November. The critical (survey) week runs from Monday through Sunday. Data on total unemployment covering all the constituent territories of the Russian Federation other than the Chechen Republic are compiled in accordance with International Labour Organization (ILO) standards. Data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Mexico Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1973 To Dec 1986
Monthly From Jan 1987 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Source: Banco de Mexico.
Notes: Data are disseminated in percentages of the labor force and relate to persons aged 12 years and over, male and female, who are unemployed, and have actively sought to engage in some economic activity in the four weeks prior to the week of the survey or up to eight weeks, provided that they are available to start work immediately. The conceptual framework follows the guidelines recommended by the International Labor Organization (ILO). The data are monthly averages and are seasonally adjusted. The source of this information is the "National Survey of the Urban Employment", which is obtained monthly at the house level for the 44 main urban areas of the country. By economic activity, the information is presented at the following level: agriculture, livestock, forestry, and fishing; extractive and electricity industry; transformation industry; construction; commerce; services; communications and transports; and government.

Name: Poland Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1927 To Jan 1990
Monthly From Feb 1990 To Dec 2020
Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on registered unemployment, expressed as the number of unemployed persons. "Unemployed persons" are defined as persons having no employment and not attending any full-time school, capable of work, ready to take up full-time employment, and registered in a labour office, if these persons: (1) are aged 18 or more; (2) are aged less than 60 for women or less than 65 for men; (3) has not acquired the right to retirement pay or pension resulting from an inability to work, does not receive a rehabilitation benefit, pre-retirement allowance or benefit, a sick, maternity or child-care benefit; (4) is not the owner or holder of agricultural real estate with on area of agricultural land exceeding 2 convertible ha; or  is not subject to retirement and pension insurance from full-time work due to being a spouse or a member of an agricultural household with an area of agricultural land exceeding 2 convertible ha; (5) has not undertaken any non-agricultural activity or is not subject, on the basis of separate regulations, to obligatory social insurance with the exception of the farmers' social insurance; (6) does not obtain monthly income  exceeding a half amount of minimum remuneration, with the exception of  interests from financial means gathered on bank accounts; (7) does not receive, on the basis of regulations concerning family allowances, a  nursing allowance, or allowance complementary to a family benefit due to a single parenthood and loosing rights to unemployment benefit after expiring of the legal period of its receiving  and (8) fulfill other conditions mentioned in the Act on  Promoting Employment and Labour Market Institutions on 20 April 2004 (Uniformed Text Journal of Law No. 99, item 1001 of 1 May 2004). Until May 2004 the obligatory was the Law on Employment and Combating Unemployment dated on 14 December 1994   (Uniformed text, Journal of Law No. 58, item 514 of 7 March 2003). The data on registered unemployment are measured at the end of the reference month and are compiled by the CSO on the basis of the administrative records of Labour Offices. Detailed data are disseminated broken down by sex, level of education, by duration of unemployment, job offers, occupation, industry, and by regional levels (voivodships and poviats). The data are not seasonally adjusted. Source: Eurostat. Metadata: Source: Central Bureau of Statistics. Notes: Data are disseminated on the number (in thousands) of unemployed persons in the de jure population and on the number of unemployed as a percentage of the labour force. "Unemployed persons" are defined as persons who had not worked for even one hour during the determinant week, who had actively sought work during the four weeks that preceded that week, and who were available for work during the determinant week. The data are obtained from quarterly sample surveys of households conducted in accordance with the "Current International Recommendations on Labour Statistics", ILO. Approximately 12,000 households are sampled each quarter. The reference period for the data is the average for the month. Trend data which are computed using monthly series that have been seasonally adjusted and adjusted for trading days and festivals are also disseminated.

Name: Hungary Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1992 To Dec 1995
Monthly From Jan 1996 To Nov 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Data are disseminated on the number of unemployed and the unemployment rate. "Unemployed persons" are defined as those who were not employed during the reference week; and (a) had actively looked for work at any time during the four weeks prior to the reference week; and (b) were available for work within two weeks following the reference week; or (c) were supposed to begin a new job within 30 days. Active job search is defined as including the following: contacting public or private employment offices to find a job, applying to employers directly, inserting or answering advertisements, asking friends or relatives, or other methods.
The data are derived from a household survey relating to the non-institutional population aged 15-74 (that is, people in hospitals, prisons and homes for the aged are excluded from the data). Since 1998 the survey covers 32,000 households nationwide. (Prior to that year the survey covered 24,000 households nationwide.) Since January 1998 the sample has consisted of three statistically equal sub-samples for each of the three months of the quarter. The households are selected on a rotation basis: any household entering the survey sample group at any point in time is expected to provide labour market information for six consecutive quarters, and is then permanently excluded from the survey sample group.
The reference date for the data had been the week, running from Monday to Sunday, containing the 12th day of the month until 2003, since then the survey is continuous, practically every week is a reference week. The survey is conducted according to International Labour Office concepts, definitions and classifications. The data are not seasonally adjusted. Source: Eurostat. Eurostat collects data from the statistical agencies of the 27 member countries of the European Economic Community, candidate countries (Macedonia, Croatia and Turkey), EFTA countries (Iceland, Norway, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) as well as other countries (Japan, Australia, United States). Name: Iceland Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1957 To Dec 1969
Monthly From Jan 1970 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Source: Directorate of Labour, Iceland

Notes: Statistics on registered unemployment are published for the total number of unemployment days within each month, the average number of unemployed during the month, the number registered unemployed as on the last day of each month, and as an unemployment rate, calculated as the total number of unemployment days divided by the number of days in the actual month excluding Saturdays and Sundays.

Unemployment days are defined as the number of standard workdays (8 hours) that unemployed or underemployed persons registered at employment agencies and unemployment registry offices throughout the country would wish to work. Unemployment rates are calculated as the unemployment days converted into man years, and divided by the total workforce expressed in man years.
All persons between 16 and 69 years of age in all sectors of the economy have the right to register as unemployed. An unemployed person is defined as one who is not employed but wishes to be. A person who is unemployed and seeks a full-time job is considered 100% unemployed, but a person who is unemployed and seeks part time work (for example, 50%) is considered partly unemployed (in the case of the example, 50% unemployed). An underemployed person is one who wishes for more work than he/she currently has, up to a maximum of eight hours per day, or 40 hours per week. Unemployment days are thus the difference between the wished for working days of unemployed and underemployed persons, and the actual working days of underemployed persons. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Luxembourg Unemployment Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 1983 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Definition: Data refer to registered unemployed residents of Luxembourg seeking work of at least 20 hours work per week through the Labour Administration Offices and who are immediately available for such work.
Coverage: Unemployed persons aged 16 to 64 are covered by the statistics.
Collection: Data are available from the monthly count of the Labour Administration Offices records of registered jobseekers.
Calculation: Monthly figures refer to the end of the period. Annual and quarterly data are averages of monthly figures.

Source: Statistical Office of Luxembourg (STATEC)


Standardised unemployment rates, Per cent
Definition: The standardised unemployment rate refers to the number of unemployed persons as a per cent of the civilian labour force. Civilian labour force consists of civilian employees, the self-employed, unpaid family workers and the unemployed. The definitions for unemployment and labour force conform with definitions adopted by the 13th Conference of Labour Statisticians, which are generally referred to as the ILO guidelines. Under these guidelines the unemployed are persons of working age who, in a specified period, are without work and are both available for and are actively seeking work. The data are based on the results of the household labour force survey.

Monthly From Jun 2001 To Jan 2020
Metadata: Notes: Unemployment Data are disseminated as a percentage of the labour force. The data source is the Permanent Employment Survey (EPE) conducted by the National Institute of Statistics and Data Processing (INEI) for metropolitan Lima. An “unemployed person” is defined as one aged 14 or more who was not working but was actively seeking a job at the time of the survey. The survey has been conducted every month since March 2001, and the reference period is the previous week in the case of each person interviewed. The definition of unemployment is in accordance with the International Labor Organization which establishes that a person is considered unemployed if three conditions are simultaneously met: not working at all, available for work and searching for a job. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Metadata: Notes: Data are disseminated on the number of unemployed persons. The data are obtained from the quarterly Labor Force Survey on a sample of 30,000 households. One part of the questionnaire refers to the employment status of the members of the household as well as — where it comes to the unemployed — the duration of the unemployment. In addition, there is a distinction between the cases of those who loose their jobs and those who are unemployed for first time. The LFS is a continuous survey providing quarterly results. The reference period for employment is the last week before the week of the day of interview. The definition adopted corresponds to those recommended by the ILO and adopted at the EU level by EUROSTAT. The term 'unemployed' includes persons aged 15 years or older who are out of work, seeking for work and available to start working (within the next two weeks). Data on unemployment are disseminated as numbers of unemployed persons, and as unemployment rates. The data are not seasonally adjusted. Source: Eurostat. Name: Ireland Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1939 To May 1983
Monthly From Jun 1983 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Data are based on the Quarterly National Household Survey (QNHS) which replaced the annual Labour Force Survey (LFS) with effect from September 1997. The new survey covers a sample of 39,000 private households (about 3.3% of all households) each quarter. As in the LFS, estimates of the numbers employed and unemployed are compiled according to two classifications:
(a) The International Labour Organisation (ILO) recommended basis; and
(b) The national Principal Economic Status (PES) basis.
Under the International Labour Organisation (ILO) classification, an unemployed person is one who, in the survey reference week was without work, was currently available for work and who had taken specific steps to find work in the preceding four weeks. Source: Eurostat. Periodicity:

Monthly From Oct 1984 To Dec 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Data are disseminated on unemployment as numbers of unemployed people, and as unemployment rates. "Unemployed persons" are defined as all people who are out of work, seeking work and available for work during the survey week. The "unemployment rate" is defined as the number of unemployed persons in relation to the total active population. The data are obtained from the "InquÃ©rito ao Emprego" (Labour Forces Survey [LFS]) which uses the harmonized European methodology. The survey covers the entire country of Portugal and presently uses a sample of approximately 21,000 households obtained from the master sample based on the 1991 Census. All individuals, with a minimum age of 15, resident and living in private households, are observed. The reference period is a given week. Weekly interviews are conducted over a 13-week period during the quarter to cover the 21,000 households. The data represent the average for the quarter.
The data are not seasonally adjusted. Source: Eurostat. Name: Ukraine Unemployment Rate
Periodicity:
Monthly From Dec 1996 To Jun 2018
Quarterly From Sep 2018 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
Notes: Data are disseminated on the unemployment rate, i.e., the number of unemployed persons aged 15 - 70 as a percentage of the labor force in the same age brackets (total of employed and unemployed). Data on unemployment are derived from the Labour Force Survey (LFS), which was conducted on an annual basis from 1995 to 1998 and on a quarterly basis since 1999 (due to changes in the methodology, the annual and quarterly data are not fully comparable). This household sample survey, whose methodology is closely harmonized to ILO recommendations, provides a measure of the economically active/inactive population, employment and unemployment. The survey covers the population of reference age between 15 and 70 years old but excludes non-residents, persons on compulsory military service and professional military personnel (provided they live in barracks), persons who live in institutional buildings (prisons, hospitals for mentally ill persons, hospital for lepers etc) and persons away from their households for more than three months. The definition of unemployment used in the Labour Force Survey closely follows international standards, in particular the definition that adopted by the International Conference of Labour Statisticians and those used by Eurostat. ILO unemployed comprise persons aged 15 - 70 years (registered and non-registered in employment services), who meet the following three criteria:
- "did not have work (profitable employment)";
- "actively looked for a work or tried to organize an own business over the last 4 weeks prior the survey" i.e. made some steps during last four weeks to find paid work or start own business;
- "were available to start work in the next two weeks", i.e. to start paid work as employee or at own enterprise in the next two weeks. Unemployed also included those who do not look for a job, because they have already found it and have agreement to start the work within a certain period of time, or who are in training organized by state employment service. Unemployment rate is calculated as the ratio of unemployed persons aged 15 - 70 to the economically active population in the same age brackets (total of employed and unemployed). The survey is carried out quarterly (since 1999) during the last month of the quarter under report. The data refer to the surveyed data for the last month of the quarter are published. The data are not seasonally adjusted.

Name: Thailand Unemployment Rate
Periodicity: Monthly From Jan 2001 To Jan 2020
Metadata:
Source: International Monetary Fund. Notes: Data are disseminated on the total unemployment rate as a percentage of the labor force. "Unemployed persons" are defined as being persons, 15 years of age and over, who during the survey week did not work even for one hour, had no jobs, business enterprises, or farms of their own, from which they were temporarily absent, but were available for work. Persons in this category include: (1) those who had been looking for work during the preceding 30 days; and (2) those who had not been looking for work because of illness or the belief that no suitable work was available, or were waiting to take up a new job, or were waiting on the agricultural season or other reasons.
Prior to 1998, labor force statistics cover the entire country, including both urban and rural workers and are complied by the National Statistical Office (NSO) twice a year. The first round survey is conducted in February coinciding with the non-agricultural season, and the second round is in August corresponding to the agricultural season. Due to the increasing demand of quarterly data for formulating plans and policy, the survey has been conducted 4 time a year in February, May, August, and November, since 1998. And since 2001, the survey has been conducted on monthly basis, with the period of data collection on 1st-12th of each month.
The reference period of the survey is the last week of the month prior to the month in which the survey as conducted. (For example, the reference period for the February survey is the last week of January.) Since 2001, the reference period is the last seven days before interview's date. The data are not seasonally adjusted.
